export const notes = "\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h3>Section 1: Singapore's Rainforest History</h3>\n  <p>Singapore's tropical rainforest has undergone dramatic transformation since the colonial era, making the remnant patches that survive today extraordinarily precious.</p>\n  <div class=\"stat-callout\">\n    <strong>Timeline of Forest Loss</strong>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>1819:</strong> Rainforest covered virtually the entire island of Singapore when Stamford Raffles established a British trading post.</li>\n      <li><strong>1882:</strong> Only about 7% of Singapore still forested \u2014 rapid clearance for rubber and gambier plantations drove near-total deforestation within 60 years.</li>\n      <li><strong>Present:</strong> Only ~3% of original primary rainforest remains \u2014 one of the world's most dramatic deforestation stories in a small territory.</li>\n    </ul>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <strong>Remaining Primary Rainforest Patches</strong>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Bukit Timah Nature Reserve (BTNR)</strong> \u2014 163 ha of primary forest</li>\n      <li><strong>Central Catchment Nature Reserve (CCNR)</strong> \u2014 ~2,000 ha, largest nature reserve in Singapore</li>\n      <li>Combined BTNR + CCNR: ~4,000 ha \u2014 known as the \"green lungs\" of Singapore</li>\n    </ul>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"sg-spotlight\">\n    <strong>Singapore's Unique Global Status</strong><br>\n    Singapore is one of only <strong>two cities in the world</strong> with a primary rainforest within its boundaries. The other city is <strong>Rio de Janeiro</strong> (Tijuca Forest, Brazil). This makes Singapore's forests of global scientific significance.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"exam-tip\">\n    <strong>Exam Tip:</strong> When asked about Singapore's forest history, remember the key statistics: virtually 100% (1819) \u2192 7% (1882) \u2192 3% (present). The dramatic drop between 1819 and 1882 was driven by plantation agriculture (rubber and gambier), not urban development.\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h3>Section 2: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve (BTNR)</h3>\n  <p>BTNR is one of the world's most biodiverse small forest fragments, containing more tree species per hectare than the entire North American continent.</p>\n  <div class=\"stat-callout\">\n    <strong>Key Facts</strong>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Area:</strong> 163 ha \u2014 very small but incredibly biodiverse</li>\n      <li><strong>Highest point:</strong> Bukit Timah Hill \u2014 163.63 m (highest natural point in Singapore)</li>\n      <li><strong>Established:</strong> 1883 (one of the world's oldest nature reserves)</li>\n      <li><strong>ASEAN Heritage Park:</strong> Designated 2011 \u2014 recognises regional ecological significance</li>\n    </ul>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <strong>Biodiversity</strong>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Over <strong>1,250 plant species</strong> and more tree species per hectare than entire North American continent</li>\n      <li>841 flowering plant species, 400+ animal species</li>\n      <li><strong>Singapore freshwater crab (Johora singaporensis):</strong> Endemic \u2014 found ONLY in BTNR streams</li>\n      <li><strong>Raffles' Banded Langur:</strong> Critically endangered primate \u2014 only ~60 remain in Singapore</li>\n    </ul>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"case-study\">\n    <strong>Eco-Link@BKE</strong>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>What:</strong> Wildlife crossing bridge over Bukit Timah Expressway (BKE)</li>\n      <li><strong>Opened:</strong> 2013</li>\n      <li><strong>Purpose:</strong> Connects BTNR to CCNR \u2014 allows animals to cross safely between reserves</li>\n      <li><strong>Cost:</strong> S$14.4 million</li>\n      <li><strong>Design:</strong> 62 m wide \"hourglass\" shape \u2014 narrows at the road crossing, widens at forest edges</li>\n      <li><strong>Significance:</strong> First wildlife overpass of its kind in Asia</li>\n    </ul>\n    <p>BTNR is a completely isolated forest fragment surrounded by urban development. Without the Eco-Link, animals are unable to move between reserves, reducing genetic diversity and long-term survival chances.</p>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"exam-tip\">\n    <strong>Exam Tip:</strong> The Eco-Link@BKE is a key Singapore case study for \"habitat fragmentation\" and \"ecological connectivity.\" Note its year (2013), cost (S$14.4 million), width (62 m), and that it is the first of its kind in Asia.\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h3>Section 3: Central Catchment Nature Reserve (CCNR)</h3>\n  <p>CCNR is Singapore's largest nature reserve and performs a critical dual function \u2014 water catchment and nature conservation.</p>\n  <div class=\"stat-callout\">\n    <strong>Key Facts</strong>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Area:</strong> ~2,000 ha (largest nature reserve in Singapore)</li>\n      <li><strong>Reservoirs:</strong> MacRitchie Reservoir, Lower Pierce Reservoir, Upper Pierce Reservoir</li>\n      <li><strong>Dual function:</strong> Water catchment (1st National Tap) + nature conservation</li>\n      <li><strong>Connection to BTNR:</strong> Via Eco-Link@BKE (opened 2013)</li>\n    </ul>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <strong>Key Features and Wildlife</strong>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>TreeTop Walk:</strong> 250 m free-standing suspension bridge through forest canopy at 25 m height \u2014 allows visitors to experience the forest at canopy level</li>\n      <li><strong>Wildlife:</strong> Wild boar, long-tailed macaques, smooth-coated otter, reticulated python</li>\n      <li><strong>Adjacent facilities:</strong> Singapore Zoo and Night Safari contribute to species conservation</li>\n    </ul>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"sg-spotlight\">\n    <strong>Water + Nature: A Dual Function</strong><br>\n    CCNR's forested catchment area protects water quality in Singapore's reservoirs (the \"1st National Tap\"). The intact forest reduces sedimentation and pollution, meaning the forest serves both ecological and strategic national water security functions. This dual value strengthens the case for conservation.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"exam-tip\">\n    <strong>Exam Tip:</strong> When asked to justify why CCNR should be conserved, mention BOTH functions \u2014 biodiversity conservation AND water catchment/national water security. Two distinct reasons are stronger than one.\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h3>Section 4: Global Conservation Strategies</h3>\n  <p>Four main strategies are used globally to conserve tropical rainforests. Each has distinct methods, examples, advantages, and limitations.</p>\n\n  <div class=\"compare-grid\">\n    <div class=\"compare-col\">\n      <strong>Strategy 1: Forest Protection (National Parks)</strong>\n      <p><em>Method:</em> Legally designate areas as protected; ban or restrict logging, mining, development.</p>\n      <p><em>Examples:</em> Daintree NP (Australia), Yasuni NP (Ecuador), Amazon National Forest (Brazil)</p>\n      <p><em>Pros:</em> Prevents direct destruction; internationally recognised; clear legal framework.</p>\n      <p><em>Cons:</em> Enforcement difficult; local communities lose access to resources; doesn't address root causes (poverty/demand).</p>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"compare-col\">\n      <strong>Strategy 2: Regulated/Sustainable Logging</strong>\n      <p><em>Method:</em> Selective logging, reduced-impact logging (RIL), Forest Stewardship Council (FSC) certification.</p>\n      <p><em>Process:</em> Only matured trees above minimum diameter felled; roads minimised; replanting required.</p>\n      <p><em>Pros:</em> Allows timber industry to continue; provides income; minimal impact if done properly.</p>\n      <p><em>Cons:</em> \"Sustainable\" often poorly enforced; roads cause secondary deforestation; slower forest recovery.</p>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"compare-col\">\n      <strong>Strategy 3: Rehabilitation and Reforestation</strong>\n      <p><em>Method:</em> Replanting cleared areas with native tree species; restoring degraded land.</p>\n      <p><em>Examples:</em> Singapore's NParks; Costa Rica increased forest cover from 21% (1987) to 52% (2021).</p>\n      <p><em>Pros:</em> Increases forest cover; sequesters carbon; restores biodiversity over time.</p>\n      <p><em>Cons:</em> Plantation forests (single species) \u2260 old-growth; takes decades; may fail if root pressures remain.</p>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"compare-col\">\n      <strong>Strategy 4: Public Education and Consumer Pressure</strong>\n      <p><em>Method:</em> Education campaigns; sustainable labelling (RSPO palm oil, FSC timber); boycotts; social media.</p>\n      <p><em>Examples:</em> Greenpeace campaigns; RSPO (Roundtable on Sustainable Palm Oil); No Deforestation pledges.</p>\n      <p><em>Pros:</em> Addresses root cause (consumer demand); can change behaviour at scale; low cost.</p>\n      <p><em>Cons:</em> Slow to produce results; difficult to enforce supply chains; risk of greenwashing.</p>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"exam-tip\">\n    <strong>Exam Tip:</strong> Know the full name and abbreviation for key bodies: FSC = Forest Stewardship Council (sustainable timber certification); RSPO = Roundtable on Sustainable Palm Oil. Both are examples of consumer pressure / sustainable labelling working through market mechanisms rather than legal enforcement.\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h3>Section 5: Evaluation Framework for Conservation</h3>\n  <p>Evaluating conservation strategies requires examining effectiveness, cost, who bears the burden, and whether root causes are addressed.</p>\n  <div class=\"formula\">\n    <strong>Evaluation Criteria</strong><br>\n    1. <strong>Effectiveness:</strong> Does it actually stop deforestation? Short-term vs. long-term impact?<br>\n    2. <strong>Cost:</strong> Who pays? Can poorer countries afford it? Should wealthy nations contribute?<br>\n    3. <strong>Root causes:</strong> Does it address poverty, debt, and trade policy \u2014 or only the symptoms?<br>\n    4. <strong>Limitations:</strong> Political will, corruption, enforcement capacity in developing nations.<br>\n    5. <strong>International cooperation:</strong> Deforestation in Brazil affects global climate \u2014 global problem needs global solutions.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"case-study\">\n    <strong>REDD+ Programme</strong>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Full name:</strong> Reducing Emissions from Deforestation and forest Degradation</li>\n      <li><strong>Mechanism:</strong> UN programme that pays developing countries to keep forests standing</li>\n      <li><strong>How it works:</strong> Countries are paid per tonne of CO2 not released into the atmosphere</li>\n      <li><strong>Significance:</strong> Provides economic incentive for forest conservation \u2014 addresses the financial root cause</li>\n    </ul>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"case-study\">\n    <strong>Debt-for-Nature Swaps</strong>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>What:</strong> Wealthy countries cancel developing country debt in exchange for commitment to forest protection</li>\n      <li><strong>Logic:</strong> Developing countries often clear forests to generate export income to repay debts \u2014 removing the debt removes the pressure</li>\n      <li><strong>Example:</strong> USA has done debt-for-nature swaps with countries in Latin America and Africa</li>\n    </ul>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"exam-tip\">\n    <strong>Exam Tip:</strong> For \"evaluate\" questions, use the structure: Advantage \u2192 Disadvantage \u2192 Overall judgement. Example: \"While forest protection is effective in preserving existing biodiversity, it fails to address the root economic causes of deforestation, such as poverty and debt. A more comprehensive approach combining protection with alternative livelihoods would be more sustainable.\"\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h3>Section 6: Singapore Green Plan 2030 and NParks Conservation</h3>\n  <p>Singapore's Green Plan 2030 is a whole-of-nation sustainability agenda that balances urban development with nature conservation.</p>\n  <div class=\"sg-spotlight\">\n    <strong>Singapore Green Plan 2030: Key Goals</strong>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>City in Nature:</strong> Bring nature into urban spaces; create urban biodiversity corridors</li>\n      <li><strong>Goal:</strong> Plant 1 million trees by 2030</li>\n      <li>Expand parks and nature areas; create more ecological connectivity throughout the island</li>\n      <li>Reduce carbon emissions; promote green buildings and sustainable transport</li>\n    </ul>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <strong>NParks (National Parks Board) Conservation Work</strong>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Manages all nature reserves, parks, and green spaces in Singapore</li>\n      <li><strong>Species Recovery Programme:</strong> Active breeding and conservation of critically endangered species</li>\n      <li>Target species: Raffles' Banded Langur, Singapore freshwater crab (Johora singaporensis), Sunda Pangolin</li>\n      <li><strong>Reforestation approach:</strong> Planting more than 50 species per hectare to maximise biodiversity (vs. monoculture plantations)</li>\n    </ul>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"stat-callout\">\n    <strong>Singapore as a Global Model</strong><br>\n    Singapore demonstrates that even a small, densely urbanised city-state with extremely limited land can prioritise conservation. The \"City in a Garden\" concept integrates green spaces throughout the urban fabric \u2014 parks, park connectors, roadside greenery, and nature reserves form an interconnected green network. This contrasts with the false choice often presented between development and conservation.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"exam-tip\">\n    <strong>Exam Tip:</strong> For Singapore-specific conservation questions, link individual strategies to the Green Plan 2030 framework. Show you understand Singapore's unique constraints (small land area, high population density) and how these shape its conservation approach. The Eco-Link@BKE, Species Recovery Programme, and the 1-million-trees goal are all strong specific examples to cite.\n  </div>\n</div>\n";

